`- **${a.name}** — ${a.description}`).join("\n");this.type="System";this.name=UcWa.UCs;this.description="The primary skill for any create / read / edit / auto layout tasks. Drives the document by running JavaScript snippets against the live page with an expansive API surface.";this.Vj=Ucha.EG;this.Hr=new Set([UcDd.Pig,UcDd.sig])}get content(){let a,b;const c=(b=(a=Uc2Jg(this.document.resolve()))==null?void 0:a.properties.nX.value)!=null?b:40;return`# Script writing

Each script has two globals in scope. Every API method accepts and returns plain JSON.

- **\`document\`** — the always-available helper for document-level operations (pages, title) and simple block / line operations (add, patch, delete, move, resize, container placement). **Reach for \`document\` first** — its methods are far simpler to specify than the alternatives.
- **\`skills\`** — namespace for *loadable* APIs. Each API is described by a a skill of the same name (see **Available APIs** below). Load that skill *once* with **Load Skill** and the helper becomes callable as \`skills.<name>.<method>(...)\` — once loaded it stays loaded for the rest of the conversation, so you only ever load it once.

# Script runner contract

Each Run Script invocation runs in a fresh QuickJS sandbox — variables, listeners, and imports do **not** persist between calls. The current page and selection *do* persist (see **The current page**). The script body runs inside an \`async\` function so top-level \`await\` and top-level \`return\` are legal. If the script throws, every document change it made is reversed before the error is returned (atomic on failure). If the user or a collaborator modifies the document during an \`await\` in your script, the call aborts and reverts with a "modified externally" error.

# Workflow

- **Understand before editing.** Use \`document.read()\` (and optionally the Render tool) to learn the current page's shape before mutating it. Don't guess at ids, classes, or layout — read first.
- **Prefer a prebuilt API when one fits.** If a listed API (see **Available APIs**) covers the feature you need, load its skill once with Load Skill.
- **Prefer relative placement and contaiment** (\`nextTo\`, \`parentId\`) with the \`document\` helper when possible. \`addBlock\` returns the created id which you can use for a subsequent relative placement even inside a single script.
- **Prefer moving / modifying existing items over deleting and recreating them** — the user may panic if content temporarily disappears.
- **For multi-page work**, call \`document.navigateToPage(pageId)\` first, then run the per-page mutations.

# The current page

Most calls operate on a single page — the **current page**. It starts out as the document's first normal page; switch it with \`document.navigateToPage(id)\`. \`document.read\`, \`addBlock\`, \`addLine\`, \`patchBlock\`, \`patchLine\`, etc. all read from / write to the current page. To operate on a different page, navigate first, then run the mutation.

Your current page and current selection persist across script invocations — both live alongside, but separately from, the user's. The script runner swaps the live document into your state on entry and the user's state on exit, so you can navigate and select freely without disturbing the user.

# Render & checking your work

Use the Render tool to output an image of the current page and visually inspect it. Re-reading or re-rendering after a change is a cheap sanity check.

**The render is the source of truth for what the document looks like.** If the render looks bad, it will look bad to the user too. Never assume the render is bugged — assume your modifications did not have the intended effect.

**Caution:** Don't rely only on the render output to answer questions about the document — content may be too small to read or items may be missed. Cross-check with \`document.read()\` or API specific read methods.

# The \`document\` API

\`document\` is always available inside Run Script (no loading needed). Every method takes and returns plain JSON.

**Read**
- \`document.read(ids?)\` → \`{userContext: UserContext, agentContext: AgentContext, blocks: BlockInfo[], lines: LineInfo[], generators: GeneratorInfo[]}\`. With no \`ids\`, returns a summary of the current page; pass an \`ids\` array for additional per-item detail. A block's \`properties\` reports the current value of every key \`patchBlock\` accepts.
  - \`UserContext = {pageId?: string, selectedItemIds: string[]}\` the user's page and selection. Use this to contextualize their prompt.
  - \`AgentContext = {pageId?: string}\` the page scripts will execute in, unless changed via \`document.navigateToPage\`
  - \`BlockInfo = {id, className, label, type: 'item' | 'container', boundingBox, children?, parent?, properties?}\`
  - \`LineInfo = {id, from, to, label?, shape?, lineColor?}\` — \`from\`/\`to\` is a block id or a free \`{x, y}\`; \`shape\` is \`'elbow' | 'curve' | 'diagonal'\`.
  - \`GeneratorInfo = {id, className, children: string[]}\` — readonly. Load a skill related to the generator to to learn how to read and write to it.

**Blocks & lines**
- \`document.addBlock(spec)\` → new id | undefined. \`spec = {blockClass, label?, width?, height?, location?, properties?}\`. \`location\` is \`{x, y}\` | \`{parentId}\` | \`{nextTo, dir, padding?}\` (\`dir\`: \`'N'|'NE'|'E'|'SE'|'S'|'SW'|'W'|'NW'\`).
- \`document.patchBlock({id, ...})\` → boolean. Same fields as \`addBlock\` plus \`id\`; any subset.
- \`document.addLine({from, to, label?, shape?})\` → new id | undefined. \`from\`/\`to\` is a block id or \`{x, y}\`. The arrow goes on the \`to\` endpoint so the line visually points \`from → to\`.
- \`document.patchLine({id, from?, to?, label?, shape?})\` → boolean.
- \`document.delete(...ids)\` → count removed. Variadic; works for blocks and lines. **Prefer this over any other deletion path.**
- \`document.moveBlock(id, x?, y?, width?, height?)\` → boolean. Absolute position/size; omitted args keep current.
- \`document.resizeBlock(id, width?, height?, x?, y?)\` → boolean.
- \`document.moveBlockToContainer(id, containerId)\` → boolean. Finds the first empty grid cell inside the container. Throws if you try to move an item into a *generator* — use the generator's API to add content to it.
- \`document.listBlocks()\` → \`string[]\`. All block classes from the basic shape libraries (flowchart, containers, shapes, sticky notes, frames); pass any to \`addBlock\`. Complex shape libraries aren't listed here — load their API instead.

\`properties\` accepted by \`addBlock\` / \`patchBlock\`: \`Text\`, \`FillColor\` (\`'#rrggbb'\`), \`LineColor\` (\`'#rrggbb'\` | null), \`LineWidth\`, \`StrokeStyle\`, \`Opacity\` (0..1), \`Rotation\` (radians), \`TextAlign\`, \`TextVAlign\`, \`TextWrap\`, \`Shadow\`, \`ZOrder\`. Other keys are dropped.

Common block classes are \`StickyNote\`, \`FrameBlock\`, \`ProcessBlock\`, \`DecisionBlock\`, and \`TerminatorBlockV2\`. Discover the full list with \`document.listBlocks()\`.

The \`document\` API intentionaly only provides surface level information about generators. In Lucid, generators create our most powerful features. Often, generators can be backed by \`data\` collections.
Generators are an internal-only concept, refer to generator-powered features by the feature name.

**Document & pages** (page methods return JSON — ids and titles, never live page objects)
- \`document.getDocumentTitle()\` / \`document.setDocumentTitle(title)\` → boolean.
- \`document.getPages()\` → \`{id, title, current, isMaster}[]\` (UI order).
- \`document.getCurrentPageId()\` → the current page id (or undefined). There is no \`getCurrentPage\`; use this for the id.
- \`document.getUserContext()\` → \`{pageId, selectedItemIds}\` — the **user's** own page + selection (tracked separately from yours). Use it to act on what the user is looking at / has selected; \`navigateToPage(pageId)\` to operate there.
- \`document.navigateToPage(pageId)\` → boolean. Sets the current page for subsequent calls.
- \`document.addPage(title?)\` → new page id (and makes it current). \`document.deletePage(pageId)\` → boolean. \`document.setPageTitle(pageId, title)\` → boolean.

# Basic Style Guide

**Common sizes**
- StickyNote default size: 160×160. Stickies enforce a 1:1 or ~2:1 ratio.
- ProcessBlock's default size: 160×120.
- Grid spacing: ${String(c)} — a good value for spacing items apart and aligning sizes/positions to multiples of.

**Tips**
- **Sticky Notes**: strongly prefer the default 1:1 size. Text on a sticky auto-resizes to fit without overflowing.
- **Titles**: prefer setting the document or page title via \`document.setDocumentTitle\` / \`document.setPageTitle\` over adding a title block as content.
- **Frames** are the standard way to group content.
  - The frame's title floats 80px *above* the frame's bounding box — you can use the full bounding box for content, but *you must* remember the title's space so it doesn't overlap whatever is north of the frame.
  - When sizing a Frame, ensure it's big enough for the content you expect to place inside. (Consider the standard StickyNote/ProcessBlock/Grid Spacing sizes listed above)

# Available APIs

